He was killed during Zimbabweâ€™s war of liberation, while serving at a leper colony. Bradburne was gunned down on the side of a road in Mutemwa in north-eastern Zimbabwe exactly 40 years ago. Hundreds of people are expected to attend a church service in Mutemwa, where arguments for and against his canonisation will be heard. The son of an English vicar, Bradburne moved to then-Rhodesia in the 1960s. Living in a tin hut, often close to starvation, he cared for lepers, refusing to leave them as a civil war raged. Since his death, several people say they have been healed after praying to him, satisfying one of the conditions for sainthood in the Catholic Church. Five steps to sainthood: --BBC--